Data

Lake Monona

Data in lake-monona-winters-2023.csv is similar to that in the Lake Mendota data set from lecture, but contains freeze durations in Lake Monona, and not from Lake Mendota. There is one row from each winter from 185556 through 202223.

Variables in the data set are:

  • winter a string such as 1855-56 which specifies the winter
  • year1 the first year of the winter
  • periods the number of periods of consecutive days where the surface of Lake Monona was closed by 50% or more of ice.
  • duration the total number of days during the winter that 50% or more of the lake surface is frozen (closed by ice)
  • first_freeze the first date the lake is closed during the winter
  • last_thaw the date of the last thaw during the winter
  • decade the decade of the first winter
  • period50 a 50-year period of time
  • ff_x the number of days after June 30 of the first freeze
  • ff_cat a categorical variable of the half-month of the first freeze

Note: lecture notes had a different name than ff_x for counting the days after June 30.

Problems

  1. The following code makes a histogram of the duration variable in the Lake Monona data set.
ggplot(monona, aes(x=duration)) +
  geom_histogram(boundary = 0, binwidth = 10,
                 color = "black", fill = "white")

In approximately how many winters was the total duration where Lake Monona was at least 50% covered with ice between 40 to 70 days?

Response

count_winters = monona %>%
  filter(duration >= 40 & duration <= 70) %>%
  nrow()

count_winters # 11 winters
## [1] 11

11

  • What does the line of code geom_smooth(se=FALSE) do? (Explain what it adds to the plot; you dont need to explain details of the method.)

Response

Aids the eye in seeing patterns in the presence of over plotting by creating a smooth line; the arg se=FALSE allows for removal of the standard error line

Response

Appears roughly linear and decreasing

# - ff_cat --- a categorical variable of the half-month of the first freeze

  geom_bar(fill="lightblue", color="black")+
  labs(title="First freezes occuring over Lake Monona",

       y = "Count of occurences")

  1. Briefly explain why you needed to use the command geom_bar() and not geom_col() to make the plot in the previous problem.

We need to use geom_bar() and not geom_col() because we are only working with a single variable, where the height is proportional to the number of cases in each group; conversely, geom_col() takes 2 variables.

  1. The following chunk creates a scatter plot with ff_x on the x axis and duration on the y axis, with points colored by period50. The variable ff_x is a numerical coding of the first freeze date, counting days after June 30. For context, December 27 is 180 days after June 30. The default color scheme is changed to viridis which is friendlier to most people with various forms of color blindness. The command geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) adds a straight line instead of a curve to the plot (thats the method = "lm" argument) and because we specified period50 as a grouping variable by mapping it to the color aesthetic, separate lines are added for each group.

Add code to add a plot title and to provide informative axis labels. Following examples from lecture notes, change the title of the color legend to say Time Period instead of period50.

ggplot(monona, aes(x = ff_x, y = duration, color = period50)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, method = "lm") +
  scale_color_viridis_d(name = "Time Periods") + # renamed legend
  labs(
    title = "Relationship between First Freeze Date and Ice Duration", 
    x = "Days after June 30",
    y = "Duration of Ice Closure") +
  theme_minimal()

After making the graph, suppose that the date of the first freeze in some year was December 27, which is 180 days after June 30. Based on an examination of the graph, briefly explain how your prediction of the total duration that Lake Monona is closed by ice would differ if the winter was in the 1870s versus the present?

We see a clear downward trend in duration that the lake is closed by ice, so it is fair to conclude that the total duration Lake Monona is closed by ice would be greater in the 1870s than in the present.

  1. The previous plot used color to distinguish which points were in each 50-year period of time. Write code to plot the same data in a scatter plot, but use a different facet (use facet_wrap(), following an example in the lecture notes) for each of the four different 50-year periods of time.
ggplot(monona, aes(x = ff_x, y = duration)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, method = "lm") +
  facet_wrap(~ period50, ncol = 2) +  # Use period50 to create facets, with 2 columns
  labs(
    title = "Relationship between First Freeze Date and Ice Duration", 
    x = "Days after June 30",
    y = "Duration of Ice Closure"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Does color or faceting make it easier to compare the relationship between first date of closing with ice and the total duration of the freeze among different 50-year time periods?

I would suggest faceting, because each facet (or panel) focuses on one 50-year period, making it clear and unambiguous. Since each time period has its own panel, theres less risk of overplotting. You can also easily make horizontal or vertical comparisons on the grid. One of the cons is that it does require more space.
